        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We estimate the expected CII-158 micron line flux density in the two LAEs from their observed SFRs, using the correlation between SFR and CII-158 micron line luminosity obtained  by De Looze et al. (2011) in a sample of nearby star-forming galaxies. The relation is 

log [ SFR ] = 0.983 x log [L(CII)] - 40.12 

where the SFR is in M_\odot/yr and the CII-158 micron line luminosity L(CII) is in erg/s (De Looze et al. 2011). Using this conversion factor and the observed SFRs of the two LAEs yields peak line flux densities of 3.6 mJy for J0228-0416 and 1.6 mJy for J0248-0331, assuming line FWHMs of 300 km/s. Further, the spread in the correlation between SFR and L(CII) corresponds to an uncertainty of a factor of ~ 2 in L(CII) (see Fig. 6 of De Looze et al. 2011). We will use a conservative approach to take this spread into account, by aiming to detect the CII-158 micron line at 5 sigma significance over each of two independent channels, even if it is a factor of 2 weaker than predicted. This implies peak line flux densities of 1.8 mJy (J0228-0416) and 0.8 mJy (J0248-0331). We then require RMS noise values of 0.36 mJy (J0228-0416) and 0.16 mJy (J0248-0331) per 150 km/s channel, to achieve our sensitivity goals. We have used the ALMA sensitivity calculator to find that these can be achieved (with 34 antennas at Band-6 in Cycle 2) in on-source times of ~ 9 minutes and ~ 45 minutes, respectively, and total times, including calibration and overheads, of ~ 37 minutes and ~ 85 minutes, respectively. Our total time request is thus 2 hours, including all calibration.

We propose to use the array in its most compact configuration, with maximum baselines of 160 m, to obtain a synthesized beam of ~ 1.5'', i.e. ~ 10 kpc at the LAE redshifts. This is to ensure that we do not resolve out any line or continuum emission. Note that the multiple images of the lensed source J0248-0331 will indeed be resolved out, allowing a search for CII-158 micron emission from each location. However, the individual lensed images will remain unresolved at a resolution of ~ 1.5''.

We request the correlator be set up in TDM mode, with four 2 GHz basebands and channel widths of 31.25 MHz (i.e. velocity resolutions of 35 km/s, after Hanning smoothing). One baseband will be centred on the redshifted CII-158 micron line for each source; the search for CII-158 micron line emission will be carried out after smoothing the spectrum to velocity resolutions of 300 km/s. The remaining three 2 GHz basebands will be used to obtain sensitive image of the redshifted FIR continuum emission, to give an independent estimate of the star formation rate, unaffected by dust obscuration. The expected continuum RMS noise values would be ~ 74 micro-Jy in 9 minutes for J0228-0416, and ~ 25 micro-Jy in 45 minutes for J0248-0331. We should thus be able to detect (at 5 sigma significance) FIR luminosities of L(FIR) ~ 4e11 L_\odot in J0228-0416 and L(FIR) ~ 1.3e11 L_\odot (after correcting for the lensing magnification factor of 11.4) in J0248-0331, for a dust temperature of 36 K, a dust emissivity of 1.5 and a modified black-body spectral energy distribution (Webb et al. 2007). Our 5 sigma sensitivity to the SFR is then ~ 60 M_\odot/yr for J0228-0416 and ~ 1.7 M_\odot/yr for J0248-0331 (again, after correcting for lensing), using the conversion factors of Bell (2003). The lower limits to the SFRs, from the UV continua,  are 60 M_\odot/yr and 2.4 M_\odot/yr, similar to our 5 sigma sensitivity limits. We should thus definitely be able to detect FIR continuum emission from both LAEs (at &gt;= 5 sigma significance) and will thus be able to estimate the amount of dust obscuration in the two galaxies.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
