    <prp:abstract>We propose to use the ALMA Band-6 receivers to carry out a search for redshifted CII-158 micron line emission from two Lyman-\alpha emitters (LAEs) at z=6.027 and z=6.170. One of the targets has a high intrinsic star formation rate (SFR), ~ 60 M_\odot/yr, while the other has a low intrinsic SFR, ~ 2.4 M_\odot/yr, but a high magnification (~ 11.4) due to gravitational lensing. These are the two best candidates for redshifted CII-158 micron emission in normal galaxies at z&gt;6. The observations will allow us to (1) obtain the first detections of CII-158 micron emission from ``normal'' galaxies at z&gt;6, (2) determine the dynamical mass of the LAEs, from the width of the CII-158 micron lines, (3) estimate L(CII)/SFR in high-redshift LAEs, which will be used to plan future CII-158 micron studies of these high-z galaxies, and (4) test whether the conversion factor between L(CII) and SFR is similar in LAEs with high and low star formation rates. We request a total of 2 hours of observing time for this project, including all calibration.</prp:abstract>
